to the editor re new york 's long and sorry tradition of judicial elections editorial observer nov 14 dorothy samuels gave a fine recitation of the ills attending the current methods of electing our judges but it was not until the final paragraph that she proclaimed the ultimate remedy to be so called merit selection of state civil and supreme court judges a process requiring a change to our state 's constitution far simpler and less controversial would be electing judges on a nonpartisan basis as many other states do that improvement could be effected by legislation alone next year if desired a simple straightforward and fair system of allowing ballot access to every qualified candidate on an equal basis without party names or symbols would help to remove the pernicious influence of party bosses on the composition of our judiciary in what is still essentially a one party town steven k isler staten island nov 15 2002

